<TITLE> Now haircuts enter the language of crisis </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, April 21 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The sub-prime crisis has added almost as much to armchair investors' financial vocabulary as it threatens to do to their mortgage repayments. Newly au fait with SIVs and conduits, they now have another term at their disposal -- a haircut. The Bank of England says it will impose variable "haircuts" on assets swapped with government debt under a 50 billion pound mortgage rescue plan announced on Monday. A haircut is the percentage discount applied to the value of assets being swapped under the scheme. That means banks will not receive the same amount of government debt for the mortgage-backed securities they exchange, but less, depending on the quality of those assets. The riskier the collateral, the larger the haircut. SIVS -- structured investment vehicles -- and the even more exotic SIV-lites -- were almost unheard-of before the sub-prime crisis broke last Summer, largely because banks held them off their balance sheets. These, and conduits, are the packages that are suspected to contain the high-risk loans linked to the sub-prime market. Credit Derivatives and Collateralised Debt Obligations are the means through which those mortgages are converted into securities. Details of the Bank's haircuts can be found he
